OK - another quick update. Brazilian Portuguese and European Portuguese are different enough that they can have separate translation efforts. I've created an additional room: gitter.im/freecodecamp/BrazilianPortuguese for this.
I hope this doesn't spread our Portuguese-speaking population too thin, but I trust that we have enough passionate people to cover both versions of the Portuguese language. Thanks for your time.

@QuincyLarson thanks for clarifying, we'll use GitHub issues and the gitter channel then.

Also, for clarity, I recommend everyone just use GitHub issues. There is no need to create Facebook groups or use Asana boards - we have Gitter and GitHub issues, and those tools have been plenty for our Spanish and Russian translation efforts so far. Also, using GitHub issues is good practice, since you will probably use them every day as a web developer.

Hi everyone, sorry I'm typing in English (I don't know Portuguese). I just wanted to take a moment to introduce @jeanleonino. He is working with an organization that teaches women how to code in several major cities in Brazil. He is interested in helping us translate our curriculum into Brazilian Portuguese. 

Even though many of our challenges have Portuguese translations in place, we haven't yet created GitHub issues associated with these. I've put detailed instructions for doing this here: https://trello.com/c/a5LsOa7B/163-we-are-moving-our-translation-effort-from-trello-to-github-issues-for-each-language-we-need-to-audit-which-challenges-have-not-y

I recommend you all create such issues to make it easier to split up the translation work. 

By the way, Spanish is basically complete, and we will soon have it in place. From there, it will be quite easy for campers to "turn on" Portuguese in our  settings menu.

Thanks for your help with our translation effort!
